11. To pass to the Accentuation of the Sentence. The Iambic aad Trochaic metres‚ which Plautus and Terence employ in their dialogue- scenes, are the metres which come nearest to the language of conversation. Since the diction of these poets is patently the diction of the ordinary life of the time, and their dialogue-scenes reproduce all the varied phases of everyday speech, with its tones of banter and innuendo, of entreaty and refusal, of threatening, command and deprecation, they afford us an excellent opportunity of testing how far the sentence-accentuation was regarded in early Latin poetry.
